1
00:00:00,312 --> 00:00:05,922
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay, this is the Medford historical commission today is Monday, March 13, we will get started.

2
00:00:05,942 --> 00:00:10,371
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm going to read our disclosure here, so we can get going.

3
00:00:10,391 --> 00:00:12,295
[SPEAKER_05]: And then we'll call the meeting to order.

4
00:00:13,666 --> 00:00:20,068
[SPEAKER_05]: Pursuant to Chapter 20 of the Acts of 2021, this meeting of the City of Medford Historical Commission will be conducted via remote means.

5
00:00:20,668 --> 00:00:26,490
[SPEAKER_05]: Members of the public who wish to access the meeting may do so by using the Zoom link provided for in the agenda.

6
00:00:27,310 --> 00:00:30,091
[SPEAKER_05]: No in-person attendance of members of the public will be permitted.

7
00:00:30,571 --> 00:00:35,092
[SPEAKER_05]: Any participation in any public hearing during this meeting shall be by remote means only.

8
00:00:39,278 --> 00:00:42,841
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay, we have a full agenda tonight so we're going to get started.

9
00:00:42,861 --> 00:00:47,225
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm off the top is 28 Grove Street.

10
00:00:47,865 --> 00:00:51,408
[SPEAKER_05]: Tonight we're going to be having a preferably preserved hearing for this property.

11
00:00:52,289 --> 00:00:53,830
[SPEAKER_05]: Just to recap how we got here.

12
00:00:56,690 --> 00:01:01,091
[SPEAKER_05]: Two months ago, we accepted an application for partial demolition at 28 Grove Street.

13
00:01:01,671 --> 00:01:04,892
[SPEAKER_05]: Last month, we had a significance hearing.

14
00:01:04,912 --> 00:01:21,477
[SPEAKER_05]: And just to remind everybody what significance means, it means that the property is either importantly associated with one or more historic persons or events, or with the broad architectural, cultural, political, economic, or social history of the city or the Commonwealth, or

15
00:01:22,037 --> 00:01:33,942
[SPEAKER_05]: that it is historically or architecturally important in terms of period, style, method of building construction, or association with an important architect or builder, either by itself or in the context of a group of buildings.

16
00:01:34,602 --> 00:01:39,364
[SPEAKER_05]: Last month, the board found that 28 Grove Street was historically significant.

17
00:01:40,184 --> 00:01:46,407
[SPEAKER_05]: So tonight we are going to have a hearing to determine whether or not there should be an 18-month demolition delay put on the property.

18
00:01:47,488 --> 00:01:48,308
[SPEAKER_05]: for the project.

19
00:01:48,889 --> 00:02:04,641
[SPEAKER_05]: And just to remind folks what preferably has preserved means the designation preferably preserved means that the commission has determined after an open public hearing that the demolition of the building under review would be detrimental to the architectural or historical heritage of the city of Medford.

20
00:02:05,542 --> 00:02:15,644
[SPEAKER_05]: And just to remind everybody, the Medford Historical Commission does not and will not consider the building's condition or any safety issues when determining whether a building is to be preferably preserved.

21
00:02:15,885 --> 00:02:18,505
[SPEAKER_05]: Only the building commissioner can address those issues.

22
00:02:23,246 --> 00:02:29,868
[SPEAKER_05]: So commissioners, I will take a motion one way or the other for this property and then we'll start the discussion.

23
00:02:32,820 --> 00:02:33,320
[SPEAKER_05]: Go ahead, Ryan.

24
00:02:34,101 --> 00:02:38,063
[SPEAKER_11]: Motion to make 28 Grove Street declared preferably preserved.

25
00:02:39,304 --> 00:02:41,926
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay, that motion has been made.

26
00:02:41,966 --> 00:02:42,626
[SPEAKER_05]: Is there a second?

27
00:02:42,646 --> 00:02:43,887
[SPEAKER_05]: I'll second.

28
00:02:44,508 --> 00:02:45,348
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay, thank you, Kit.

29
00:02:46,669 --> 00:02:48,350
[SPEAKER_05]: All right, so we'll go around.

30
00:02:48,430 --> 00:02:57,356
[SPEAKER_05]: We will do commissioner comments first, and then I'll open it up to any public comments, and we'll kind of circle back from that.

31
00:02:57,776 --> 00:03:00,298
[SPEAKER_05]: So Ryan, why don't you start us off since you made the motion?

32
00:03:01,106 --> 00:03:10,451
[SPEAKER_11]: Sure, this is a what I perceive to be a really a building with integrity remaining.

33
00:03:11,852 --> 00:03:18,476
[SPEAKER_11]: You know it requires some work but that's outside of our purview and, of course, it seems like the owner is going to renovate this building.

34
00:03:19,797 --> 00:03:21,258
[SPEAKER_11]: rather than totally tear it down.

35
00:03:21,418 --> 00:03:34,067
[SPEAKER_11]: But I just want to point out the reason for my motion is that in looking at the building, it seems to maintain a lot of historic fabric that provides a detail and a direction for this building.

36
00:03:34,127 --> 00:03:38,070
[SPEAKER_11]: It's got its original wooden siding, windows, doors.

37
00:03:38,670 --> 00:03:43,993
[SPEAKER_11]: It's got a beautiful front porch, and more importantly, it matches the existing surrounding neighborhood.

38
00:03:44,093 --> 00:03:51,278
[SPEAKER_11]: This is a part of a large development that was put up in the early 20th century, and it's vital to the streetscape.

39
00:03:51,338 --> 00:03:58,122
[SPEAKER_11]: And it seems like there's a number of buildings in West Medford around this one that have been rehabilitated over the years.

40
00:03:58,222 --> 00:04:05,787
[SPEAKER_11]: So I'm interested in seeing this building rehabilitated to some sort of new use that doesn't destroy its integrity.

41
00:04:09,193 --> 00:04:09,953
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you, Ryan.

42
00:04:11,114 --> 00:04:12,315
[SPEAKER_05]: Kit, I'll come to you next.

43
00:04:14,596 --> 00:04:16,797
[SPEAKER_06]: I think Ryan just gave a really nice summary.

44
00:04:16,817 --> 00:04:22,420
[SPEAKER_06]: And I also feel like the conversation that we had about this at our last meeting was pretty comprehensive, actually.

45
00:04:22,440 --> 00:04:29,364
[SPEAKER_06]: And I remain convinced that it is preferably preserved.

46
00:04:31,025 --> 00:04:31,586
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you, Kit.

47
00:04:32,586 --> 00:04:33,987
[SPEAKER_05]: Doug, I'll come to you next.

48
00:04:40,090 --> 00:04:41,811
[SPEAKER_05]: Oh, Doug, I can't hear you.

49
00:04:41,871 --> 00:04:42,451
[SPEAKER_05]: Is it just me?

50
00:04:43,131 --> 00:04:43,391
[SPEAKER_10]: No.

51
00:04:44,072 --> 00:04:44,632
[SPEAKER_11]: I can't hear.

52
00:04:44,652 --> 00:04:47,313
[SPEAKER_10]: There's something funny on your sound there, Doug.

53
00:04:54,015 --> 00:04:55,056
[SPEAKER_05]: Doug, I'll come back to you.

54
00:04:56,536 --> 00:04:57,577
[SPEAKER_05]: Peter, you want to jump in?

55
00:04:58,597 --> 00:05:04,900
[SPEAKER_10]: I think Ryan summarized it quite well.

56
00:05:07,112 --> 00:05:08,593
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't have much to add to that.

57
00:05:08,893 --> 00:05:14,756
[SPEAKER_10]: I have done some work in other houses, a similar house in the neighborhood.

58
00:05:16,637 --> 00:05:24,021
[SPEAKER_10]: And I can just echo what he said about, it was just a block or two over.

59
00:05:24,081 --> 00:05:27,103
[SPEAKER_10]: There's a number of houses similar to this one in the neighborhood.

60
00:05:27,965 --> 00:05:31,266
[SPEAKER_10]: And the neighborhood itself maintains quite a bit of integrity.

61
00:05:31,686 --> 00:05:36,447
[SPEAKER_10]: And, you know, it would be great to keep that continuity going.

62
00:05:37,008 --> 00:05:37,248
[SPEAKER_10]: So.

63
